<DOC><DOCNO> AP880511-0293 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-11-88 1004EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a PM-ReligionRoundup Adv13   05-11 0608</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Religion Roundup, Adv 13,0630</SECOND><NOTE>$adv13</NOTE><NOTE>For release Fri PMs May 13, or thereafter</NOTE><DATELINE>WHEATON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A theologian for the National Associationof Evangelicals says carbon-14 tests on the Shroud of Turin willnot affect evangelical belief in Christ's resurrection, whateverthe results.   ``It is no more than an interesting investigation,'' says theRev. Arthur Climenhaga, chairman of NAE's theological committee.``Even if proof could be offered that the Shroud of Turin was theshroud of Christ, that would be no more than an additional artifactin the historical evidences of Christ's resurrection _ already sowell attested.''   The Vatican is allowing the carbon-14 tests on bits of theshroud, preserved in Turin, Italy, and bearing the image of acrucified man, to determine its age, and whether it dates to thetime of Christ.   Results of the tests are expected later this year.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The American Bible Socierty reports that itsU.S. distribution of Scriptures in 1987 totalled 116,155,119copies, up 16 million or 15.6 percent over the year before.</TEXT><DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Several countries reportedly havedropped suspended broadcasts of defrocked TV evangelist JimmySwaggart after the scandal involving him with a prostitute.   Among stations or networks cited as dropping his program werethose in Trinidad and Tobago, South Africa, Jamaica and Swaziland.   Swaggart has said he will begin broadcasting again May 25,defying orders of the denomination that ousted him not to preachfor at least a year.</TEXT><DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The United Methodist Publishing Househas developed a policy on AIDS in the workplace, saying the diseaseis not spread by casual contact and protecting the jobs and privacyof any employes who have it.   If ``unable to perform their normal job duties because of theirillness,'' workers with AIDS would be given disability leaves, thepolicy says. Employees who refuse to work alongside people withAIDS could go on unpaid leaves or apply for other publishing housejobs.   The policy is ``to protect the rights of all our employees,''says Stephen C. Tippens, a vice president, who adds that so far, nocases of AIDS have been reported among the agency's 1,300 employes.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Although studies have indicated that mostsuccessful career women are single, divorced or childless, a studyof successful Jewish career women find that a majority are marriedand have children.   In the study sponsored by the American Jewish Committee andLilith Magazine, a Jewish feminist quarterly, questionaireresponses from 944 Jewish career women showed 603 had married andhad children.   Most ``were embedded in a `superwoman' syndrome, daily jugglingmultiple role obligations,'' the findings say.</TEXT><DATELINE>MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A ``Bible Card,'' about the size ofa business card, has on it the entire Bible in microfilm form, saysits producer, ThemeCards, Inc.   It says l00,000 copies are being turned out for people to carryas a reminder of faith, although immense magnification would berequired to read the contents.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   U.S. Roman Catholic bishops have consistentlyopposed U.S. military aid to the Contra rebels in Nicaragua, butthe bishops applaud current U.S. humanitarian aid to them.   It is ``a sign of hope that all sides may now be workng to forgea lasting and just peace,'' says Archbishop John L. May of St.Louis, president of the National Conference of Bishops.   He said in a letter to Nicaragua's Cardinal Miguel Obando yBravo that the aid both would help war victims and sustain thecontras while the peace process goes forward.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs May 13.</NOTE></DOC>